{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":370,"text":"I'm a lexicographer."},{"time":1928,"text":"I make dictionaries."},{"time":3682,"text":"And my job as a lexicographer"},{"time":5121,"text":"is to try to put all the words possible \ninto the dictionary."},{"time":8841,"text":"My job is not to decide what a word is;\nthat is your job."}]},{"cues":[{"time":14924,"text":"Everybody who speaks English \ndecides together"},{"time":17821,"text":"what's a word and what's not a word."},{"time":20153,"text":"Every language is just a group of people\nwho agree to understand each other."},{"time":25305,"text":"Now, sometimes when people are trying \nto decide whether a word is good or bad,"},{"time":29909,"text":"they don't really have a good reason."},{"time":31677,"text":"So they say something like,\n\"Because grammar!\""},{"time":34488,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":36862,"text":"I don't actually really care about grammar\ntoo much -- don't tell anybody."}]},{"cues":[{"time":40425,"text":"But the word \"grammar,\" actually,\nthere are two kinds of grammar."},{"time":43564,"text":"There's the kind of grammar\nthat lives inside your brain,"},{"time":46434,"text":"and if you're a native \nspeaker of a language"},{"time":48543,"text":"or a good speaker of a language,"},{"time":50132,"text":"it's the unconscious rules that you follow\nwhen you speak that language."},{"time":53531,"text":"And this is what you learn when\nyou learn a language as a child."},{"time":56552,"text":"And here's an example:"},{"time":58189,"text":"This is a wug, right?"},{"time":59714,"text":"It's a wug."},{"time":61775,"text":"Now there is another one."},{"time":63471,"text":"There are two of these."},{"time":64634,"text":"There are two ..."},{"time":65923,"text":"Audience: Wugs."},{"time":67107,"text":"Erin McKean: Exactly! You know \nhow to make the plural of wug."},{"time":70820,"text":"That rule lives in your brain."},{"time":72301,"text":"You never had to be taught this rule, \nyou just understand it."},{"time":75250,"text":"This is an experiment that was invented\nby a professor at [Boston University]"},{"time":78879,"text":"named Jean Berko Gleason back in 1958."},{"time":82024,"text":"So we've been talking about this \nfor a long time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":85049,"text":"Now, these kinds of natural rules \nthat exist in your brain,"},{"time":88563,"text":"they're not like traffic laws,\nthey're more like laws of nature."},{"time":92785,"text":"And nobody has to remind you to obey \na law of nature, right?"},{"time":96140,"text":"When you leave the house in the morning, \nyour mom doesn't say,"},{"time":99093,"text":"\"Hey, honey, I think\nit's going to be cold, take a hoodie,"},{"time":101972,"text":"don't forget to obey the law of gravity.\""},{"time":104439,"text":"Nobody says this."},{"time":106325,"text":"Now, there are other rules that are more\nabout manners than they are about nature."},{"time":113182,"text":"So you can think of a word as like a hat."},{"time":116046,"text":"Once you know how hats work,"},{"time":118296,"text":"nobody has to tell you, \n\"Don't wear hats on your feet.\""},{"time":121163,"text":"What they have to tell you is, \n\"Can you wear hats inside?\n"},{"time":124507,"text":"Who gets to wear a hat?"},{"time":126264,"text":"What are the kinds of hats\nyou get to wear?\""},{"time":129396,"text":"Those are more of the second kind \nof grammar,\n"},{"time":131818,"text":"which linguists often call usage, \nas opposed to grammar."}]},{"cues":[{"time":136121,"text":"Now, sometimes people use this kind of \nrules-based grammar"},{"time":140255,"text":"to discourage people from making up words."},{"time":143043,"text":"And I think that is, well, stupid."},{"time":145727,"text":"So, for example, \npeople are always telling you,"},{"time":148993,"text":"\"Be creative, make new music, do art, \ninvent things, science and technology.\""},{"time":154233,"text":"But when it comes to \nwords, they're like,"},{"time":156271,"text":"\"Don't! No. Creativity stops right here,\nwhippersnappers. Give it a rest.\""},{"time":161004,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":162421,"text":"But that makes no sense to me."},{"time":164142,"text":"Words are great.\nWe should have more of them."},{"time":166474,"text":"I want you to make\nas many new words as possible."},{"time":170530,"text":"And I'm going to tell you six ways that\nyou can use to make new words in English."}]},{"cues":[{"time":175550,"text":"The first way is the simplest way."},{"time":177639,"text":"Basically, steal them from other \nlanguages."},{"time":179862,"text":"[\"Go rob other people\"]\n(Laughter)"},{"time":183936,"text":"Linguists call this borrowing,"},{"time":185764,"text":"but we never give the words back ,\nso I'm just going to be honest"},{"time":188824,"text":"and call it stealing."},{"time":190784,"text":"We usually take words for things \nthat we like, like delicious food."},{"time":194154,"text":"We took \"kumquat\" from Chinese,\nwe took \"caramel\" from French."},{"time":197944,"text":"We also take words \nfor cool things like \"ninja,\" right?"},{"time":200851,"text":"We took that from Japanese,"},{"time":202301,"text":"which is kind of a cool trick because \nninjas are hard to steal from."},{"time":205570,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":207684,"text":"So another way that you \ncan make words in English"},{"time":210944,"text":"is by squishing two \nother English words together."},{"time":213885,"text":"This is called compounding."},{"time":215572,"text":"Words in English are like Lego:"},{"time":217082,"text":"If you use enough force, \nyou can put any two of them together."},{"time":220447,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":222832,"text":"We do this all the time in English:"},{"time":224627,"text":"Words like \"heartbroken,\" \"bookworm,\" \n\"sandcastle\" all are compounds."},{"time":230105,"text":"So go ahead and make words like\n\"duckface,\" just don't make duckface."},{"time":233606,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":235835,"text":"Another way that you can make words \nin English is kind of like compounding,"},{"time":239848,"text":"but instead you use so much force\nwhen you squish the words together"},{"time":244899,"text":"that some parts fall off."},{"time":246534,"text":"So these are blend words, \n"},{"time":248215,"text":"like \"brunch\" is a blend \nof \"breakfast\" and \"lunch.\""},{"time":252064,"text":"\"Motel\" is a blend of \"motor\" and \"hotel.\""},{"time":254796,"text":"Who here knew that \"motel\" \nwas a blend word?"},{"time":257737,"text":"Yeah, that word is so old in English"},{"time":259581,"text":"that lots of people don't know that \nthere are parts missing."},{"time":262692,"text":"\"Edutainment\" is a blend \nof \"education\" and \"entertainment.\""},{"time":266987,"text":"And of course, \"electrocute\" is a\nblend of \"electric\" and \"execute.\""},{"time":272197,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":274007,"text":"You can also make words\nby changing how they operate."},{"time":277328,"text":"This is called functional shift."},{"time":278941,"text":"You take a word that acts \nas one part of speech,"},{"time":281242,"text":"and you change it into another \npart of speech."},{"time":283522,"text":"Okay, who here knew that \"friend\"\nhasn't always been a verb?"},{"time":288881,"text":"\"Friend\" used to be noun \nand then we verbed it."},{"time":293076,"text":"Almost any word in English can be verbed."},{"time":296345,"text":"You can also take adjectives \nand make them into nouns."},{"time":298978,"text":"\"Commercial\" used to be an adjective \nand now it's a noun."},{"time":302705,"text":"And of course, you can \"green\" things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":305151,"text":"Another way to make words\nin English is back-formation."},{"time":308489,"text":"You can take a word and you can\nkind of squish it down a little bit."},{"time":311747,"text":"So for example, in English we had the word\n\"editor\" before we had the word \"edit.\""},{"time":316568,"text":"\"Edit\" was formed from \"editor.\""},{"time":318320,"text":"Sometimes these back-formations \nsound a little silly:"},{"time":321065,"text":"Bulldozers bulldoze, butlers butle \nand burglers burgle."},{"time":325453,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":327278,"text":"Another way to make words in English"},{"time":329050,"text":"is to take the first letters of something\nand squish them together."},{"time":332220,"text":"So National Aeronautics and Space \nAdministration becomes NASA."},{"time":335251,"text":"And of course you can do this \nwith anything, OMG!"}]},{"cues":[{"time":338963,"text":"So it doesn't matter how silly \nthe words are."},{"time":344602,"text":"They can be really good words of English."},{"time":346608,"text":"\"Absquatulate\" is a perfectly \ngood word of English."},{"time":350626,"text":"\"Mugwump\" is a perfectly \ngood word of English."},{"time":353489,"text":"So the words don't have have to sound \nnormal, they can sound really silly."}]},{"cues":[{"time":358067,"text":"Why should you make words?"},{"time":360256,"text":"You should make words because every word"},{"time":362397,"text":"is a chance to express your idea and get \nyour meaning across."},{"time":366918,"text":"And new words grab people's attention."},{"time":369514,"text":"They get people to focus on what \nyou're saying"},{"time":372163,"text":"and that gives you a better chance to get \nyour meaning across."},{"time":375427,"text":"A lot of people \non this stage today have said,"},{"time":378376,"text":"\"In the future, you can do this,"},{"time":379938,"text":"you can help with this, you can \nhelp us explore, you can help us invent.\""},{"time":383471,"text":"You can make a new word right now."},{"time":385100,"text":"English has no age limit."},{"time":387433,"text":"Go ahead, start making words today,"},{"time":389859,"text":"send them to me, and I will put them \nin my online dictionary, Wordnik."},{"time":393546,"text":"Thank you so much."},{"time":394835,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}